 stored in the same place but accessed at different times.</p></li><li><p>Physical Reservoir Computing (PRC): This method involves exciting inert materials to perform computations. Different computations can be extracted from the same material by exciting it in different ways. This approach allows the same material to embody different computations.</p></li><li><p>Soft Robotics: Soft robots are made from flexible materials that allow them to perform multiple functions simultaneously. This includes sensation, actuation, computation, power storage, and power generation.</p></li></ol><p>The text suggests that these technologies could lead to significant advancements in robotics, including the development of robots that can simultaneously perform external behaviors and internal computations. This would blur the traditional distinction between the "body" (behavior-generating components) and the "brain" (computation-generating components) of a robot.</p><p>It's also noted that these technologies could have implications for our understanding of biological systems. For instance, the discussion suggests that both the body and the brain may be capable of polycomputing, challenging the traditional distinction between these two entities. The authors also suggest that our understanding of computation may need to be rethought in light of these technologies.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disab