e, where a single genomic information can result in multiple different anatomical, physiological, and behavioral forms through epigenetics.</p><p>The Xenobots are given as an example of massive phenotypic plasticity, a key aspect of polycomputing. They are self-assembled organisms made from frog skin cells that exhibit a range of autonomous behaviors. The fact that they are not genetically modified but can perform such a range of functions illustrates the concept of polycomputing in biological systems.</p><p>The paper then discusses how evolution creates generic problem-solving machines rather than solutions for specific problems, which is a crucial aspect of polycomputing. It suggests that evolution leverages the polycomputing capabilities of biological systems to allow the exploration of novel possibilities without disrupting the functioning of existing systems.</p><p>In a section called "Evolving Polycomputing," the authors discuss how polycomputing architectures allow for faster evolution. They use the example of a tadpole's eye which, even when placed in the wrong position, can still provide vision because the cells can adapt to their environment and perform their function.</p><p>The paper concludes that while the evolutionary pressure to make existing materials perform multiple tasks is immense, there's still much to learn about how this pressure leads to polycomputing. Understanding how materials can be overloaded with new functions without negatively impacting existing ones is a key question in this field.</p><p>Figure 6 further illustrates the concept of biological morphogenesis, showing how organisms adapt to their circumstances and attempt to create viable organisms with whatever is at hand. It illustrates the ability of organisms to adapt to novel conditions and maintain their functionality, a testament to the polycomputing ability of biological systems.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center