r science, suggesting that the transition from an analog device to a computer is just a shift in the relative payoffs for two different formalisms.</li></ol><p>6.1. Agency and persuadability: The authors argue that recognizing the degree of agency within certain dynamical systems or physical materials is an important next step. They also discuss the concept of persuadability, which is the range of techniques suitable for interacting with different systems.</p><p>6.2. The impact of observer frames: The authors propose that a polycomputing system may be able to respond to multiple observers trying to persuade it to do different things simultaneously.</p><p>6.3. Becoming a computer: The authors discuss how difficult it can be to determine whether something is a computer, or at what point it becomes one. They argue that biological and non-biological systems change over time, which complicates the issue. They suggest that as technology and our understanding of biological systems progress, we may need to accept that many systems house multiple selves, each with varying degrees of computational and agential potential.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points