ea that our physiological states can influence our mental states is known as embodied cognition. According to this perspective, our bodies are not just passive vehicles for our brains, but actively contribute to our cognitive processes.</p><p>For instance, consider the physiological symptoms of fear – your heart rate increases, your palms might get sweaty, and you might feel a pit in your stomach. According to some theories, such as the James-Lange theory of emotion, you don't run because you're afraid; instead, you're afraid because you notice your body's fear response.</p><p>Translating this to the concept of computation or information processing, you could argue that our brains are constantly processing multiple streams of information in parallel – not just from our senses, but also from our internal physiological states. This would indeed be a kind of polycomputation, in which multiple computations are happening at the same time and influencing each other.</p><p>This idea might also tie back to your earlier point about Null Convention Logic (NCL). Just as an NCL circuit uses null wavefronts to separate valid computations from invalid ones, our brains might use physiological signals to help distinguish between different emotional states or cognitive processes. For example, the feeling of hunger might serve as a kind of 'null wavefront' that resets our cognitive state and directs our attention towards finding food.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span>