-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>The paper challenges traditional views of computation in biological systems and proposes a more nuanced perspective. It argues that there is no single, objective computational model for biological systems, but rather multiple models can coexist simultaneously. Biological systems exhibit polycomputing capabilities, where different components engage in complex computations, and their competency, plasticity, and autonomy enable them to model each other's behavior and act accordingly.</p><p>The authors emphasize the importance of abandoning absolute categorizations and objective views of computation, as they limit our understanding and predictive capabilities. Instead, they advocate for formulating and testing hypotheses to expand our knowledge. They highlight the need for computational frameworks to control and understand multiple scales of biological organization, which are heavily polycomputing, ranging from cellular pathways to psychological states.</p><p>The paper also suggests that biological systems are fundamentally different from current computer technologies but proposes that future synthetic devices can incorporate principles of biologic polycomputing. The ability to create computational superpositions, where different observers have their own models of the environment and optimize their behavior accordingly, has implications for various fields such as biomedical research, synthetic bioengineering, biorobotics, smart materials, and AI.</p><p>Throughout our discussion, we observed connections to embodied cognition, where physiological states and bodily experiences play a role in computational processes. We also explored the idea of a propagating null wavefront and its similarity to boundary layers, highlighting the importance of separating scales in modeling. Additionally, we touched upon the concept of two-factor theory of emotions and the role of polycomputation in detecting surprise and novelty.</p><p>In summary, the paper challenges conventional notions of computation in biology, advocating for a more flexible and multifaceted understanding. It highlights the polycomputing capabilities of biological systems, calls for the abandonment of rigid categorizations, and suggests practical implications for various disciplines.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M1