19.9441 10.8122 19.9254 10.8098 19.9058V10.6071C10.8107 9.18295 11.2173 7.78848 11.9819 6.58696C12.7466 5.38544 13.8377 4.42659 15.1275 3.82264C16.4173 3.21869 17.8524 2.99464 19.2649 3.1767C20.6775 3.35876 22.0089 3.93941 23.1034 4.85067C23.0427 4.88379 22.937 4.94215 22.8668 4.98473L14.9024 9.58517C14.7025 9.69878 14.5366 9.86356 14.4215 10.0626C14.3065 10.2616 14.2466 10.4877 14.2479 10.7175L14.2424 21.9419ZM16.071 17.9991L20.4018 15.4978L24.7325 17.9975V22.9985L20.4018 25.4983L16.071 22.9985V17.9991Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg></div></div></div><div class="relative flex w-[calc(100%-50px)] flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3 lg:w-[calc(100%-115px)]"><div class="flex flex-grow flex-col gap-3"><div class="min-h-[20px] flex flex-col items-start gap-4 whitespace-pre-wrap break-words"><div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>The application of the TAME framework to somatic cognition, specifically in the context of morphogenesis, reveals unconventional agency and cognitive processes at play. By examining phenomena in morphogenesis that go beyond traditional molecular explanations, we can uncover the cognitive nature of collective cellular activity.</p><p>Morphogenesis, the process of building complex structures in organisms, is typically viewed as a purely emergent outcome of local rules and complexity science. However, the TAME framework suggests that there is more to morphogenesis than simple emergence. Morphogenesis involves goal-directed activity, where individual cells cooperate to achieve specific anatomical target morphologies. This goal-directed nature of morphogenesis meets James' test for minimal mentality, as it involves fixed ends (target morphology) with varying means (cellular activity).</p><p>One example that demonstrates the goal-directed activity in morphogenesis is the transformation of tadpoles into frogs. When the craniofacial structures of tadpoles are artificially altered, the organs move in novel paths to reach the correct frog face positions, resulting in largely normal frogs. This shows that cells modify their activity context-dependently to achieve a specific anatomical target morphology. Similarly, frog legs induced to regenerate can create the correct final form through alternative developmental steps. These examples highlight the intelligent nature of morphogenesis, where cells modify their behavior to reach specific anatomical states.</p><p>Pattern memory is a key component of somatic cognition in morphogenesis. Deer antlers and planarian flatworms demonstrate the ability to remember and reproduce specific patterns. In deer, wounds made on a branched antler structure result in ectopic tines growing at the same location in subsequent years. This requires cells to sense and remember the location of a transient damage event within the antler structure. Planarian flatworms, when cut into multiple pieces, regenerate precisely what is missing at each location, indicating the ability to remember and reproduce correct anatomical structures. These examples illustrate experience-dependent, re-writable pattern memory, where the target morphology is re-written within standard hardware.</p><p>The multi-scale competency of growth and form in morphogenesis is another characteristic of somatic cognition. Molecular mechanisms can be flexibly deployed to achieve the same large-scale goal in morphogenesis. For example, newt kidney tubules can adapt to unexpected size changes by scaling the cell number or having a single cell wrap around itself to form a proper lumen. This plasticity and coarse-graining over subunits' states resemble the autonomy and collective cognition seen in neuroscience.</p><p>There are significant parallels between morphogenetic and cognitive systems, further supporting the notion of somatic cognition. Mirror neurons and somatotopic representation, commonly associated with brains, can also be observed in response to injury in limbs. The plasticity and communication dynamics that scale individual neural cells into a coherent self are evolutionary traits honed in the context of morphogenic control.</p><p>Understanding somatic cognition in morphogenesis has practical implications. It has led to the discovery of reprogrammable head number in planarian flatworms and pre-neural roles for neurotransmitters. It explains teratogenicity and patterning defects observed in human channelopathies and suggests the utility of gap junction blockers as general anesthetics. The TAME framework also predicts specific overlaps between genes involved in morphogenesis and cognition, which can be explored through bioinformatics. Additionally, the trainability of morphogenesis through reinforcement learning holds promise for regenerative medicine, as it offers a path to control anatomical structures without relying solely on genomic editing.</p><p>Overall, the application of the TAME framework to somatic cognition in morphogenesis reveals the cognitive nature of collective cellular activity. It highlights goal-directed behavior, pattern memory, and multi-scale competency as key aspects of somatic cognition. Understanding these processes in morphogenesis can provide insights into regenerative medicine and expand our understanding of cognitive systems beyond traditional</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-