. This will contribute to a deeper understanding of exploration as a capacity for exploring better possibilities, complementing problem-solving and stress-guided paradigms.</p></li><li><p>Connection with the robustness paradox: Exploring the relationship between noise, stochasticity, and robustness in physiological and genetic systems, and how anatomical homeostasis and error correction strategies influence stability and precision. This will provide insights into the engineering principles emerging from the evolutionary process.</p></li><li><p>Cross-level analysis: Developing tools, such as information theory, to detect when a system acts as a module within a larger system and to gauge the cognitive capacity and goals of that larger system. This allows for a better understanding of how goals shape the option space available to individual agents.</p></li><li><p>Exploring embodiment and time-scale: Expanding the framework to handle a broader range of systems in terms of embodiment and time-scale. For example, viewing evolutionary lineages as agents in fitness space and exploring how collective intelligence can be deployed in an evolutionary search process.</p></li><li><p>Enlarging the cognitive boundary: Understanding how to expand a system's cognitive cone laterally, allowing for a greater capacity to care and contribute to larger-scale goals. This involves exploring the concept of responsibility in collective behavior and "group karma."</p></li></ol><p>These are some of the directions in which the TAME framework and related research are moving, aiming to provide a more inclusive and comprehensive understanding of cognition across different systems and scales.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox