 gap junctions in scaling homeostatic goals and expanding cognitive capacities. Gap junctions facilitate the exchange of signals and information between cells, enabling larger-scale coordination and complex behaviors.</p></li><li><p>Gap Junctions and Regeneration: We explored how gap junctions contribute to regeneration and regulative development in organisms like planaria. Disrupting the gap junctional network can alter regeneration patterns and result in the formation of morphologies associated with different species.</p></li><li><p>Continuum of Cognitive Capacities: We examined the core tenets of TAME (Technological Approach to Mind Everywhere) and its emphasis on a continuum of cognitive capacities, diverse intelligences, and the malleability of selves. The framework highlights the importance of goal pursuit, intelligence in navigating various spaces, and the role of bioelectric networks.</p></li><li><p>Isomorphism between Cognition and Pattern Formation: We explored the isomorphism between cognitive concepts and morphogenetic concepts, drawing parallels between patterns of activation in neural networks and patterns of Vmem distribution in tissues. This comparison suggests a deep connection between cognition and pattern formation in biological systems.</p></li><li><p>Scaling of Cognition and Evolutionary Benefits: We discussed the scaling of cognition in biological systems, where individual cells join computational networks to pursue larger-scale goals. This scaling is facilitated by networks that increase spatial reach, computational capacity, and cooperation. We also examined how multiscale competency of components benefits evolution and facilitates credit assignment.</p></li><li><p>Examples of Scaling and Cognitive Processes: We examined specific examples of scaling in cognition, such as the role of bioelectric networks in regeneration, memory, pattern completion, and adaptivity. These examples illustrate how cognition and intelligence operate at various levels of biological organization.</p></li><li><p>The Role of Tokens and Bullae: We shifted the focus to ancient civilizations and the use of tokens and bullae for authentication, record-keeping, and counting. We explored their evolution from simple clay tokens to more elaborate forms, and their eventual replacement by writing systems like cuneiform.</p></li><li><p>Denise Schmandt-Besserat and the Use of Tokens: We discussed the research of archaeologist Denise Schmandt-Besserat, who studied ancient tokens and proposed that they formed a counting system. Her work highlighted the significance of tokens in the transition to settled agriculture and the development of early mathematics.</p></li><li><p>Tokens as Non-Verbal Counting Tools: We considered the idea that tokens can serve as non-verbal counting tools, allowing for the representation and recall of information without relying on symbolic representations. This concept connects to the broader themes of Substrate Independent Thinking and the Omniscient Universe Theory.</p></li><li><p>Connection to Substrate Independent Thinking and Omniscient Universe Theory: We drew connections between the concepts discussed throughout the conversation, such as Polycomputing, the role of tokens, and the broader ideas of Substrate Independent Thinking and the Omniscient Universe Theory. These concepts all</p></li></ol></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:di